Trend analysis of leatherback turtles nesting in Florida, Puerto Rico, and St Croix with Kelly Stewart.

```{r}
rm(list=ls())
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(readr)
library(lubridate)
library(jagsUI)
library(bayesplot)
library(stringr)
```

Get data;

```{r}
col.def <- cols(ID = col_integer(),
                year = col_integer(),
                beach = col_character(),
                latitude = col_double(),
                distance = col_double(),
                days_week = col_integer(),
                days_year = col_integer(),
                nests = col_integer())

nest.counts <- read_csv("data/FL_PR_STX.csv", col_types = col.def) %>% 
  mutate(beach_f = as.factor(toupper(beach)))

```


Try fitting growth models - we can use the same model as the last paper as required/requested by KS. Other state-space models also were fit but the results were not welcomed...

```{r}
# order the data by latitude
data.MS.df <- data.frame(beach = data.MS$beach,

ns <- data.MS.df %>% group_by(beach = as.factor(beach)) %>%
  summarise(n = n())

lat.MS.df <- data.frame(beach = seq(1, data.MS$nbeach),
                        latc = data.MS$latc,
                        latc2 = data.MS$latc2,
                        n = ns$n)  
  
data.MS.df %>% left_join(lat.MS.df, by = "beach") -> tmp
data.MS.df <-  arrange(tmp, latc)

```



```{r}
MCMC.params <- list(n.samples = 100000,
                    n.burnin = 50000,
                    n.thin = 5,
                    n.chains = 5)

parameters <- c("a0", "a1", "beta", "B.hat", "a1pc",
                "mu.a0", "mu.a1",
                "rea0", "rea1",
                "delta1", "delta2",
                "sigma.e", "Sigma.B",
                "sigma.a0", "sigma.a1",
                "floridapc", "probP", "deviance",
                "Devobs", "Devpred")

MCMC.params$model.file = "models/Model_JAGS_rSlope_rInt_3Covs.txt"


if (!file.exists("RData/JAGS_out_Dist_rSlope_rInt_3Covs_MS.rds")){
  jm.MS <- jags(data = data.MS,
                #inits = inits,
                parameters.to.save= parameters,
                model.file = MCMC.params$model.file,
                n.chains = MCMC.params$n.chains,
                n.burnin = MCMC.params$n.burnin,
                n.thin = MCMC.params$n.thin,
                n.iter = MCMC.params$n.samples,
                DIC = T, 
                parallel=T)
  
  saveRDS(jm.MS, file = "RData/JAGS_out_Dist_rSlope_rInt_3Covs_MS.rds")
  
} else {
  jm.MS <- readRDS("RData/JAGS_out_Dist_rSlope_rInt_3Covs_MS.rds")
}

summary(jm.MS)
```

The MS dataset converges fine. Compare results to the publication.

```{r}
summary.MS.df <- data.frame(jm.MS$summary) %>% rownames_to_column("Parameter")

# find the beach-specific growth rate in percent
#mcmc_trace(jm.MS$samples, pars = "a1pc[38]")

summary.MS.df %>% filter(str_detect(Parameter, pattern = "a1pc")) %>%
  rownames_to_column("beach") %>%
  transmute(beach = as.numeric(beach),
            mean_a1pc = mean,
            sd_a1pc = sd,
            low25_a1pc = X2.5.,
            median_a1pc = X50.,
            upper975_a1pc = X97.5.)-> a1pc

a1pc %>% left_join(lat.MS.df, by = "beach") %>%
  arrange(latc) -> a1pc

summary.MS.df %>% filter(str_detect(Parameter, pattern = "mu.a1")) %>%
  rownames_to_column("beach") %>%
  transmute(beach = as.numeric(beach),
            mean_mu.a1 = mean,
            sd_mu.a1 = sd,
            low25_mu.a1 = X2.5.,
            median_mu.a1 = X50.,
            upper975_mu.a1 = X97.5.)-> mu.a1

mu.a1 %>% left_join(lat.MS.df, by = "beach") %>%
  arrange(latc) -> mu.a1
```

Results look similar to what were reported in the publication. They are not identical, which is a bit concerning... but they are in the same ballpark. 

So, the code is working fine.

Start here next to make the data comparable between the old and new and run analyses again. Extract the same data from the newly obtained data. These should be identical to what were analyzed above... 


```{r}

nest.counts %>% select(ID, latitude) %>% 
  group_by(ID) %>%
  summarise(latitude = first(latitude)) %>%
  mutate(latc = latitude - mean(latitude),
         latc2 = latc^2) -> lat.dat 

X <- cbind(log(nest.counts$distance),
           nest.counts$days_week - median(nest.counts$days_week),
           nest.counts$days_year - median(nest.counts$days_year))

# beach ID = 12 is missing from the earlier data... 
nest.counts %>% filter(year < 2009) %>%
  mutate(ID2 = as.numeric(as.factor(ID)))-> nest.counts.2008

nest.counts.2008 %>% select(ID2, latitude) %>% 
  group_by(ID2) %>%
  summarise(latitude = first(latitude)) %>%

                nest.counts.2008$days_week - median(nest.counts.2008$days_week),

jags.data.2008 <- list(N = length(nest.counts.2008$nests),

} else {
```

This explains the problem... so, what went wrong? 

Perhaps some beaches have no data? In the paper, there were 68 beaches, whereas I have 73. Take a look at the number of data points per beach:

```{r}
nest.counts.2008 %>% group_by(ID2) %>% 
  summarise(n = n(),
            name = first(beach_f),
            latitude = first(latitude)) %>%
  arrange(latitude) -> sample.size.2008

#write_csv(sample.size.2008, path = "data/sample_size_2008.csv")
head(sample.size.2008)
```

There are more beaches in the new dataset than in the paper. Additional ones are... there are 10 of them. I found these by manually comparing the output file (sample_size_2008.csv) and the paper. In the paper, there are supposed to be 68 beaches (p. 265)... So, they don't match!
